#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:419
msgid "JavaScript limits in library files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:421
msgid ""
"If you're not familiar with JavaScript, say if you're a C/C++ programmer and "
"just using emscripten, then the following issues probably won't come up, but "
"if you're an experienced JavaScript programmer you need to be aware some "
"common JavaScript practices can not be used in certain ways in emscripten "
"library files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:427
msgid ""
"To save space, by default, emscripten only includes library properties "
"referenced from C/C++. It does this by calling ``toString`` on each used "
"property on the JavaScript libraries that are linked in. That means that you "
"can't use a closure directly, for example, as ``toString`` isn't compatible "
"with that - just like when using a string to create a Web Worker, where you "
"also can't pass a closure. (Note that this limitation is just for the values "
"for the keys of the object passed to ``addToLibrary`` in the JS library, "
"that is, the toplevel key-value pairs are special. Interior code inside a "
"function can have arbitrary JS, of course)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:438
msgid ""
"To avoid this limitation of JS libraries, you can put code in another file "
"using the ``--pre-js`` or ``--post-js`` options, which allow arbitrary "
"normal JS, and it is included and optimized with the rest of the output. "
"That is the recommended approach for most cases. Another option is another "
"``<script>`` tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:443
msgid ""
"Alternatively, if you prefer to use a JS library file, you can have a "
"function replace itself and have it called during initialization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:474
msgid ""
"A `__postset` is a string the compiler will emit directly to the output "
"file. For the example above this code will be emitted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:499
msgid ""
"You can also put most of your code in the ``xxx__postset`` strings. The "
"example below each method declares a dependency on ``$method_support`` and "
"are otherwise dummy functions. ``$method_support`` itself has a "
"corresponding ``__postset`` property with all the code to set the various "
"methods to the functions we actually want."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:541
msgid ""
"Note: If you are using node 4.1 or newer you can use multi-line strings. "
"They are only used at compile time not runtime so output will still run in "
"ES5 based environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:545
msgid ""
"Another option is to put most of your code in an object, not a function,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:583
msgid "See the `library_*.js`_ files for other examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:587
msgid ""
"JavaScript libraries can declare dependencies (``__deps``), however those "
"are only for other JavaScript libraries. See examples in `/src <https://"
"github.com/emscripten-core/emscripten/tree/main/src>`_ with the name format "
"**library_*.js**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:591
msgid ""
"You can add dependencies for all your methods using ``autoAddDeps(myLibrary, "
"name)`` where myLibrary is the object with all your methods, and ``name`` is "
"the thing they all depend upon. This is useful when all the implemented "
"methods use a JavaScript singleton containing helper methods. See "
"``library_webgl.js`` for an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:597
msgid ""
"The keys passed into `addToLibrary` generate functions that are prefixed by "
"``_``. In other words ``my_func: function() {},`` becomes ``function "
"_my_func() {}``, as all C methods in emscripten have a ``_`` prefix. Keys "
"starting with ``$`` have the ``$`` stripped and no underscore added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:606
msgid "Calling JavaScript functions as function pointers from C"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:608
msgid ""
"You can use ``addFunction`` to return an integer value that represents a "
"function pointer. Passing that integer to C code then lets it call that "
"value as a function pointer, and the JavaScript function you sent to "
"``addFunction`` will be called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:613
msgid "See `test_add_function in test/test_core.py`_ for an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:615
msgid ""
"You should build with ``-sALLOW_TABLE_GROWTH`` to allow new functions to be "
"added to the table. Otherwise by default the table has a fixed size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:618
msgid ""
"When using ``addFunction`` with a JavaScript function, you need to provide "
"an additional second argument, a Wasm function signature string, explained "
"below. See `test/interop/test_add_function_post.js <https://github.com/"
"emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/main/test/interop/test_add_function_post."
"js>`_ for an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:626
msgid "Function Signatures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:628
msgid ""
"The LLVM Wasm backend requires a Wasm function signature string when using "
"``addFunction`` and in JavaScript libraries. Each character within a "
"signature string represents a type. The first character represents the "
"return type of a function, and remaining characters are for parameter types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:633
msgid "``'v'``: void type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:634
msgid "``'i'``: 32-bit integer type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:635
msgid "``'j'``: 64-bit integer type (see note below)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:636
msgid "``'f'``: 32-bit float type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:637
msgid "``'d'``: 64-bit float type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:638
msgid "``'p'``: 32-bit or 64-bit pointer (MEMORY64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:640
msgid ""
"For example, if you add a function that takes an integer and does not return "
"anything, the signature is ``'vi'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:643
msgid ""
"When ``'j'`` is used there are several ways in which the parameter value "
"will be passed to JavaScript. By default, the value will either be passed as "
"a single BigInt or a pair of JavaScript numbers (double) depending on "
"whether the ``WASM_BIGINT`` settings is enabled. In addition, if you only "
"require 53 bits of precision you can add the ``__i53abi`` decorator, which "
"will ignore the upper bits and the value will be received as a single "
"JavaScript number (double).  It cannot be used with ``addFunction``.  Here "
"is an example of a library function that sets the size of a file using a 64-"
"bit value passed as a 53 bit (double) and returns an integer error code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:663
msgid ""
"Using ``-sWASM_BIGINT`` when linking is an alternative method of handling 64-"
"bit types in libraries.  ```Number()``` may be needed on the JavaScript side "
"to convert it to a usable value.  See `settings reference <https://"
"emscripten.org/docs/tools_reference/settings_reference.html?"
"highlight=environment#wasm-bigint>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:671
msgid "Access memory from JavaScript"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:673
msgid ""
"You can access memory using :js:func:`getValue(ptr, type) <getValue>` and :"
"js:func:`setValue(ptr, value, type) <setValue>`. The first argument is a "
"pointer (a number representing a memory address). ``type`` must be an LLVM "
"IR type, one of ``i8``, ``i16``, ``i32``, ``i64``, ``float``, ``double`` or "
"a pointer type like ``i8*`` (or just ``*``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:679
msgid ""
"There are examples of these functions being used in the tests — see `test/"
"core/test_utf.in`_ and `test/test_core.py`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:682
msgid ""
"This is a lower-level operation than :js:func:`ccall` and :js:func:`cwrap` — "
"we *do* need to care what specific type (e.g. integer) is being used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:686
msgid ""
"You can also access memory 'directly' by manipulating the arrays that "
"represent memory. This is not recommended unless you are sure you know what "
"you are doing, and need the additional speed over :js:func:`getValue` and :"
"js:func:`setValue`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:691
msgid ""
"A case where this might be required is if you want to import a large amount "
"of data from JavaScript to be processed by compiled code. For example, the "
"following code allocates a buffer, copies in some data, calls a C function "
"to process the data, and finally frees the buffer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:703
msgid ""
"Here ``my_function`` is a C function that receives a single integer "
"parameter (or a pointer, they are both just 32-bit integers for us) and "
"returns an integer. This could be something like ``int my_function(char "
"*buf)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:707
msgid ""
"The converse case of exporting allocated memory into JavaScript can be "
"tricky when Wasm-based memory is allowed to **grow**, by compiling with ``-"
"sALLOW_MEMORY_GROWTH``. Increasing the size of memory changes to a new "
"buffer and existing array views essentially become invalid, so you cannot "
"simply do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:729
msgid ""
"Emscripten will refresh the canonical views like ``HEAPU8`` for you, which "
"you can use to refresh your own views:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:746
msgid ""
"Another option to avoid such problems is to copy the data, when that makes "
"sense."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:752
msgid "Affect execution behaviour"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:754
msgid ""
"``Module`` is a global JavaScript object, with attributes that Emscripten-"
"generated code calls at various points in its execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:757
msgid ""
"Developers provide an implementation of ``Module`` to control how "
"notifications from Emscripten are displayed, which files that are loaded "
"before the main loop is run, and a number of other behaviours. For more "
"information see :ref:`module`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:765
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:767
msgid ""
"Sometimes compiled code needs to access environment variables (for instance, "
"in C, by calling the ``getenv()`` function). Emscripten-generated JavaScript "
"cannot access the computer's environment variables directly, so a "
"\"virtualised\" environment is provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:772
msgid ""
"The JavaScript object ``ENV`` contains the virtualised environment "
"variables, and by modifying it you can pass variables to your compiled code. "
"Care must be taken to ensure that the ``ENV`` variable has been initialised "
"by Emscripten before it is modified — using :js:attr:`Module.preRun` is a "
"convenient way to do this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:778
msgid ""
"For example, to set an environment variable ``MY_FILE_ROOT`` to be ``\"/usr/"
"lib/test/\"`` you could add the following JavaScript to your ``Module`` :ref:"
"`setup code <module-creating>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:786
msgid ""
"Note that Emscripten will set default values for some environment variables "
"(e.g. LANG) after you have configured ``ENV``, if you have not set your own "
"values. If you want such variables to remain unset, you can explicitly set "
"their value to `undefined`. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:798
msgid "Binding C++ and JavaScript — WebIDL Binder and Embind"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:800
msgid ""
"The JavaScript methods for calling compiled C functions are efficient, but "
"cannot be used with name-mangled C++ functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:803
msgid ""
":ref:`WebIDL-Binder` and :ref:`embind` create bindings between C++ and "
"JavaScript, allowing C++ code entities to be used in a natural manner from "
"JavaScript. *Embind* additionally supports calling JavaScript code from C++."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:807
msgid ""
"*Embind* can bind almost any C++ code, including sophisticated C++ "
"constructs (e.g. ``shared_ptr`` and ``unique_ptr``). The *WebIDL Binder* "
"supports C++ types that can be expressed in WebIDL. While this subset is "
"smaller than supported by *Embind*, it is more than sufficient for most use "
"cases — examples of projects that have been ported using the binder include "
"the `Box2D`_ and `Bullet`_ physics engines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:814
msgid ""
"Both tools allow mapped items to be used from JavaScript in a similar way. "
"However they operate at different levels, and use very different approaches "
"for defining the binding:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:818
msgid "*Embind* declares bindings within the C/C++ file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:819
msgid ""
"*WebIDL-Binder* declares the binding in a separate file. This is run through "
"the binder tool to create \"glue\" code that is then compiled with the "
"project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:823
msgid ""
"There is no strong evidence that one tool is \"better\" than the other in "
"terms of performance (no comparative benchmarks exist), and both have been "
"used successfully in a number of projects. The selection of one tool over "
"the other will usually be based on which is the most natural fit for the "
"project and its build system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:832
msgid "Binding C/C++ and JavaScript - Node-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/connecting_cpp_and_javascript/Interacting-with-code.rst:834
msgid ""
"`Emnapi`_ is an unofficial `Node-API`_ implementation which can be used on "
"Emscripten. If you would like to port existing Node-API addon to WebAssembly "
"or compile the same binding code to both Node.js native addon and "
"WebAssembly, you can give it a try. See `Emnapi documentation`_ for more "
"details."
msgstr ""
